<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Assembling" class="currentChild" href="Assembling">Assembling</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
In <a title="Prepress" href="Prepress">prepress</a>, an alternate term for <a title="Image Assembly" href="Image_Assembly">image assembly</a> or <a title="Stripping" href="Stripping">stripping</a>. See <a title="Stripping" href="Stripping">Stripping</a>. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
In <a title="Binding and Finishing" href="Binding_and_Finishing">binding and finishing</a>, <em>assembling</em> refers collectively to <a title="Collating" href="Collating">collating</a>, <a title="Gathering" href="Gathering">gathering</a>, or <a title="Inserting" href="Inserting">inserting</a>—or, in other words, collecting pages or <a title="Signature" href="Signature">signature</a>s into complete sets as a prelude to binding. See <a title="Binding and Finishing" href="Binding_and_Finishing">Binding and Finishing</a>. 
</p>
<p id="l5">
In typography, the term <em>assembling</em> referred to collecting and pasting up set type onto a <a title="Mechanical" href="Mechanical">mechanical</a>. In hand-set and hot-metal typography, <em>assembling</em> referred to combining metal type slugs on a galley. 
</p>
